05238nam a22007695i 9780231547253DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019009399  a97802315472537 a10.7312/zama187402doi  a(DE-B1597)526855  a(OCoLC)1110009927  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aE185b.Z36 2019 4aE185b.Z36 2019 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a973/.04960732231 aZamalin, Alex, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlack Utopia :bThe History of an Idea from Black Nationalism to Afrofuturism /cAlex Zamalin. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b6 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction: Utopia and Black American Thought -- t1. Martin Delany’s Experiment in Escape -- t2. Turn- of- the- Century Black Literary Utopianism -- t3. W. E. B. Du Bois’s World of Utopian Intimacy -- t4. George S. Schuyler, Irony, and Utopia -- t5. Richard Wright’s Black Power and Anticolonial Antiutopianism -- t6. Sun Ra and Cosmic Blackness -- t7. Samuel Delany and the Ambiguity of Utopia -- t8. Octavia Butler and the Politics of Utopian Transcendence -- tConclusion: Black Utopia and the Contemporary Political Imagination -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWithin the history of African American struggle against racist oppression that often verges on dystopia, a hidden tradition has depicted a transfigured world. Daring to speculate on a future beyond white supremacy, black utopian artists and thinkers offer powerful visions of ways of being that are built on radical concepts of justice and freedom. They imagine a new black citizen who would inhabit a world that soars above all existing notions of the possible.In Black Utopia, Alex Zamalin offers a groundbreaking examination of African American visions of social transformation and their counterutopian counterparts. Considering figures associated with racial separatism, postracialism, anticolonialism, Pan-Africanism, and Afrofuturism, he argues that the black utopian tradition continues to challenge American political thought and culture. Black Utopia spans black nationalist visions of an ideal Africa, the fiction of W. E. B. Du Bois, and Sun Ra’s cosmic mythology of alien abduction. Zamalin casts Samuel R. Delany and Octavia E. Butler as political theorists and reflects on the antiutopian challenges of George S. Schuyler and Richard Wright. Their thought proves that utopianism, rather than being politically immature or dangerous, can invigorate political imagination. Both an inspiring intellectual history and a critique of present power relations, this book suggests that, with democracy under siege across the globe, the black utopian tradition may be our best hope for combating injustice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAfrican AmericansxIntellectual life. 0aAfrican AmericansxPolitics and government. 0aUtopias. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019 Englishz978311061017808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2019z9783110606195oZDB-23-DEG40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/zama1874040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231547253423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/c